issues.message:
### Version
- `@colyseus/sdk@0.17.39`
- TypeScript 5.x, strict mode

### Reproduction

A PUT endpoint that only declares a `body` schema — no query, no path params:

```ts
// server
export const setupMe = createEndpoint('/api/v1/players/me', {
    method: 'PUT',
    body: z.object({
        username: z.string().min(3),
        race: z.enum(PlayerRaces),
    }),
}, async (ctx) => { /* ... */ });

export default defineServer({
    routes: createRouter({ setupMe }),
    /* ... */
});
```

Client:

```ts
import { Client } from '@colyseus/sdk';
import type Server from '../../server/src/app.config';

const client = new Client<typeof Server>('http://localhost:2567');

await client.http.put('/api/v1/players/me', {
    body: { username: 'Johnny', race: PlayerRaces.DWARF },
});
```

### Expected
Typechecks. The endpoint only declared `body`, so `body` should be the only required option.

### Actual
```
error TS2769: No overload matches this call.
  Overload 1 of 2 — Type '{ body: {...} }' is missing the following properties: query, params
  Overload 2 of 2 — Argument of type '"/api/v1/players/me"' is not assignable to parameter of type 'never'.
```

The type system demands `query` and `params` on the options object, even though the endpoint never declared a query schema or any path parameters. And the second overload reports the path as `never`, so there's no way to satisfy it.

This happens for every `client.http.*` call in a typed setup — any endpoint that declares only a body triggers it.

### Workaround

Passing empty `query` and `params` satisfies the type checker and has no runtime effect:

```ts
await client.http.put('/api/v1/players/me', {
    body: { username: 'Johnny', race: PlayerRaces.DWARF },
    query: {},
    params: {},
});
```

### Suggested fix
An endpoint that declares no query schema and no path params should not require `query` / `params` on the client call. Whatever internal check decides "does this option have required fields" is currently treating an absent schema as if it had required fields — that's the piece that needs to flip.

